𝐌𝐢𝐜𝐫𝐨𝐦𝐨𝐬𝐚𝐢𝐜 𝐝𝐞𝐜𝐨𝐫𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧𝐬!
Today I would highlight one of the most exquisite ring set in Tourmaline and diamond from @sicisjewels; enveloping the Micromosaic decorations!

This remarkable and ancient technique, the brand's signature, allows to obtain tiny glass fragments with complex and varied shapes, set one by one by hand with patience and precision to create colourful and fascinating designs; the result is extraordinary, and this ring is a perfect example!
Truly a glass apart! ✨😍

#thediamondtalk #renurecommends #sicis #sicisjewels #luxuryjewelry #jewelrydesign #jewelleryart #artjewellery #micromosaic #micromosiacjewelry

Go green!💚💎
Here is one-of-a-kind jewellery!
A stunning 250cts Zambian emerald centrepiece is graciously set around kite-shaped diamonds and smaller emeralds; in addition a magnificent pair of 96 cts hexagonal shape Zambian earrings pair by @abfjewels seen at  @bahrainjewellerycentre in @jewelleryarabiabahrain 

Nothing can be more spectacular or grander than this!
Do you agree?

It was a pleasure visiting @garrard in @asiajewellers during @jewelleryarabiabahrain and view their exquisite tiara!👑

To understand what makes this company stand out let me share a brief history about them.
✨Garrard & Co. Limited, formerly called Asprey & Garrard Limited; were designers and manufacturers of luxury jewellery and silver. Interestingly, Garrard was the first official and most notably important Crown Jeweller of the United Kingdom. They have supplied jewels for Queen Victoria, and were responsible for the upkeep of British Crown Jewels, from 1843 to 2007. And that’s not all they are still responsible for the creation of many tiaras and jewels worn by the British royal family even today!! 
✨What is even more interesting is that apart from jewellery, Garrard is also known for having created some of the world’s most illustrious sporting trophies, namely the Americas Cup, the ICC Cricket World Cup Trophy and several trophies for Royal Ascot in its role as Official Trophies and Silverware Supplier, which originally dates back to the first Gold Cup in 1842.

So many feathers in one cup? No wonder Gerrard & Co. Ltd. continues to be a force to reckon with! 
#thediamondtalk #renurecommends #garrard #pearltiara #diamondtiara

I will be sharing a few of my favourite lots from their upcoming auctions in the following categories:
1️⃣ David Webb Jewels
2️⃣Van Cleef & Arpels
3️⃣ Rings & Earrings
4️⃣ Brooches & Bracelets
5️⃣ Necklaces
6️⃣ Watches and miscellaneous

Let's begin the preview with David Webb, who has been the quintessential American jeweller of highly original, modern jewellery. He is best known for distinctive, carved and enamelled animal bracelets, dramatic gold necklaces, colourful sautoirs, Maltese cross brooches and exquisite rock crystal pieces.

A visit to the National Museum Of Qatar @nmoqatar 

One of the key highlights of my today’s visit to the National Museum Of Qatar is 𝐁𝐀𝐑𝐎𝐃𝐀 𝐏𝐄𝐀𝐑𝐋 𝐂𝐀𝐑𝐏𝐄𝐓 circa 1865-70, originally commissioned as a gift for the tomb of the Prophet Muhammad. This carpet is a living testimony to the flourishing pearl trade in the past between the Persian Gulf and India.

The rectangular-shaped pearl carpet is made of a combination of silk and deer hide. It is densely embroidered overall with a design worked in strings of over 2.2 million pearls. Across the centre of the carpet, there are three large round “rosettes” placed symmetrically. The centre of the rosettes is filled with diamonds and surrounded by larger strings of Natural Pearls. There are a total of 32 smaller diamond rosettes, embellished with sapphires, rubies and emeralds set in gold, placed right around the border of the carpet. In between the smaller diamond rosettes, are found still smaller rosettes centred around ruby and surrounded by eight other rubies, all surrounded by strings of pearls.
If you are planning a visit to Qatar; I recommend to visit the National Museum Of Qatar

🇩🇪Germany finds most items from the 2019 jewellery heist! 👏
🇩🇪The German authorities confirmed that they found a “considerable portion” of items stolen in the 2019 robbery of priceless 18th-century jewels from the Green Vault museum in the Royal Palace in the eastern city of Dresden. The thieves had grabbed 21 pieces of jewellery and other valuables from the collection of the Saxon ruler Augustus the Strong, worth at least €113.8 million!

Hear it from the expert!
Who can best explain the craftsmanship and detailing other than the expert himself!

Mr Mehernosh Heeramaneck of Heeramaneck & Son, has been passionately obsessed with jewellery since his early years. He often visited museums, antique stores and high jewellery brands such as Cartier, Harry Winston and Van Cleef along with his father Mr Ardeshir Heeramaneck; and that reflects in the jewellery pieces as every Heeramaneck piece is designed and crafted around the exclusive gemstone procured by him to the highest standard.
✨A case point is this stunning Emerald and Diamond necklace. Talking about this exquisite jewellery, Mr Mehernosh Heeramaneck shared, “When we bought these emeralds we were excited because the quality of the emeralds is absolutely amazing. It’s a combination of cushion with one large octagonal emerald cut in the centre of the pendant; all certified natural Zambian emeralds. We wanted to create something which was kind of a Maharaja piece which I think turned out to be quite beautiful, super nice quality rose cut diamonds and altogether a great piece of jewellery”

It’s by taking care of the smallest of details that turns every piece of jewellery turns into a work of art!

✨Bikaner; a city in Rajasthan is famous for its majestic places, forts, unique architecture, artworks, culture and most importantly, Jadau Polki Jewellery. 
✨I would like to introduce Mohanlal Narayandas Jewellers from Bikaner who is a renowned manufacturer of the finest Polki Jadau jewellery and supplier of trendsetting bridal jewellery. Their latest collection “RAANISAA” the heirloom collection is inspired by the Maharanis of Bikaner who are the epitome of grace and elegance!
👉Wearing this jewellery on the wedding day will make the bride feel no less than a Maharani. So here is a shout-out to all the brides-to-be and their families to visit Mohanlal Narayandas Jewellers 1K26 & 1L3

Meanwhile, let me share a brief description of a few of the most commonly used jewellery terms for reference.
1️⃣ Polki-Jewellery:
The history of polki or uncut diamond jewellery can be traced back to the Mughal era. Polki jewellery is made using raw, uncut diamonds. Polki diamonds look bigger compared to faceted diamonds and brighter in appearance than Kundan.
2️⃣ Jadau Jewellery:
This term is mistakenly used to describe jewellery, but jadau isn’t jewellery; rather, it is the technique and skill used to create Kundan and Polki jewellery. ‘JAD’ means embedded, which is a method craftsmen use to make jewellery.
3️⃣ Kundan Jewellery:
Uses glass and non-diamond gemstones that are mounted onto 24k gold known as Kundan gold foils, giving them a shiny and refined appearance.

I would like to highlight a few important jewellery terms I curated from the previous edition.
1️⃣ Polki-Jewellery:
The history of polki or uncut diamond jewellery can be traced back to the Mughal era. Polki jewellery is made using raw, uncut diamond. Polki diamonds look bigger compared to faceted diamonds and brighter in appearance than Kundan.

2️⃣ Navratna Jewellery:
Navratna is a Sanskrit term for “Nine gems”. The Navartana indicates the nine planets of our solar system that governs each of the gems; The jewellery created using the nine gemstones is known as Navaratna Jewellery.

3️⃣ Meenakari Jewellery:
Meenakari jewellery is traditional Indian jewellery in which the metal is overlaid with brightly coloured designs of traditional Indian motifs like flowers, birds, leaves etc. This art was brought to Varanasi by Persian artists in the 17th century.

Bigger! Better! Greener IIJS Signature Show!
@gjepcindia 
It’s been a wonderful experience being a part of the IIJS Signature Show 2023. Today I would like to focus on the important key features of the show. 
1️⃣ QR scanner made it easy to navigate across different halls and booths, and shuttle services made the drive between the halls very convenient and smooth.
2️⃣ The theme, murmuration of starlings, is a reminder that we can achieve great success. Together we fly as one! 
3️⃣ One of the key aspects is that the show ran completely on “Green Energy” and One Earth is the Council’s first step towards making the IIJS shows completely carbon-neutral.
4️⃣ Budding Designers and Women Entrepreneurs across the country exhibited at the design gallery and a separate hall was dedicated to machinery and packaging. 
5️⃣ Saving multiple visiting cards has always been a challenge; at IIJS Signature, cards were scanned to save the contact.
7️⃣ At INNOV8 Launch Pad, the exhibitors launched their products/services and distinguished speakers from the industry conducted talks. 

Kudos to the council for focussing on these important aspects and working so hard to make this show a grand success! It was a pleasure to Connect..Collaborate.. and Grow at the IIJS, where business happens and I look forward to the next edition.

𝐌𝐚𝐥𝐚𝐜𝐡𝐢𝐭𝐞 𝐢𝐧 𝐌𝐨𝐬𝐚𝐢𝐜 𝐓𝐞𝐜𝐡𝐧𝐢𝐪𝐮𝐞𝐬!💚
At @didoni_store; a family-run business renowned for cutting and processing both precious and semi-precious hard stones, I saw exclusive Malachite objects made in Mosaic Techniques.

The mosaic technique represents one of the most complex methods of artistic processing of natural stones and implies a great mastery of stone processing.
👉Thin stone tiles of malachite, flat and different in shape, are combined by a master craftsman to form a single harmonious image. The final artefact is composed of small pieces and not of solid stone. The skill of craftsmen consists in laying the elements in such a way that the seams are invisible.
👉The next step is polishing where the glued tiles are rubbed with special grinding wheels after which the special lustre emerges from the stone!
Trust the Italians for handcrafting nothing but the best. Definitely a labour of love from Italy!🇮🇹

#thediamondtalk #renurecommends #malachite #malachitestone #malachitegreen #malachitejewelry

Museum Visit! 🇩🇪
One of the most attractive highlights from my visit to the Intergem Show was “Long Night of the Gemstones”, where institutions in Idar-Oberstein opened their doors to welcome exhibitors, visitors and citizens.

Today, I would like to highlight my visit to The German Gemstone Museum in Idar-Oberstein. 

✨The museum displayed more than 10,000 exhibits on three floors of a stylishly restored Gründerzeit villa. Here, I saw a variety of unique gemstones, minerals, gem objects, and stone carving art with originals and duplicates of historical seals, cameos and vessels whose origins date back to the Old Babylonian period. 
A few highlights from my visit are:
✨” The warrior of love” took 20 years in making and is a great example that gemstone art doesn’t always have to be a piece of jewellery. A total of 129 gemstones, lapis lazuli, chrysoprase, carnelian and tourmaline adorn the impressive unique piece.
✨A historic gemtone book from 1750-1780.
✨Lady Emerald; made from a single gemstone and “Mercedes Star” designed by Achim Grimm made of Nigeria Tourmaline. 
✨” Ptolemaic cameo” Greek agate work cameo from around 250 BC along with some spectacular cameo.

Several thousand exhibits in the German Gemstone Museum are mostly loans and donations from the gemstone industry in the Idar-Oberstein area and from friends of the museum from all over the world. You must plan a visit to the German Gemstone Museum in Idar Oberstein.

#thediamondtalk #renurecommends #idaroberstein #museumvisit

🦋During my visit to Doha, I was invited to 𝐏𝐚𝐩𝐢𝐥𝐥𝐨𝐧 𝐁𝐨𝐮𝐭𝐢𝐪𝐮𝐞; which has a jewellery collection designed by 𝐍𝐨𝐨𝐫𝐚 𝐀𝐥 𝐀𝐧𝐬𝐚𝐫𝐢.

✨I am dressed in local Qatari attire and 21kt of traditional Arabic jewellery. 
✨ Noora Al Ansari, the owner and designer of Papillon jewellery shared; 
“𝑰𝒏 𝑷𝒂𝒑𝒊𝒍𝒍𝒐𝒏 𝒘𝒆 𝒂𝒓𝒆 𝒗𝒆𝒓𝒚 𝒘𝒆𝒍𝒍 𝒌𝒏𝒐𝒘𝒏 𝒇𝒐𝒓 𝒐𝒖𝒓 𝒃𝒓𝒊𝒅𝒂𝒍, 𝒈𝒐𝒍𝒅 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒅𝒊𝒂𝒎𝒐𝒏𝒅 𝒔𝒆𝒕𝒔 𝒄𝒐𝒍𝒍𝒆𝒄𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏. Incredible pair of dragonflies made in PLIQUE-À-JOUR enamel by @faerbercollection 

Let’s discover more about the enamel technique:
✨Plique-à-jour is a French term that translates to “Letting in the Daylight”. This technique of enamel was first discovered in the 15th century by Benvenuto Cellini; it was rediscovered in France circa 1900 and wheeled to new heights during the Art Nouveau period.
✨Plique-à-jour technique is used to make enamel resemble stained glass. Here; the enamel is applied in cells similar to cloisonné but with no backing in the final product, which allows the light to shine through the transparent or translucent enamel. This enamelling technique is popularly used in the rendering of leaves, flowers, insect wings and other gossamer illusions.
✨Objects made of Plique-à-jour are fragile, rare and extremely valuable. Though created by the same enameller, each finished product is unique and incomparable!
✨Art Nouveau artists René Lalique, Lucien Gaillard along with other French and German artists used this technique in their work for producing perfume bottles, vases, jewellery, chandeliers, clocks and automobile hood ornaments during the early twentieth century.

@kimkardashian wins Diana’s amethyst Attallah Cross for $197, 453 @sothebysjewels London. 
✝️The cross-shaped pendant is of fleurée style - made distinct by flowery design details – and set with square-cut amethysts which are accented by circular-cut diamonds.
✝️The story goes; the Attallah cross was created in the 1920s by court jewellers Garrard and Princess Diana most famously wore it in October 1987, pairing it with a Catherine Walker dress, to a charity gala. 
✝️The cross was bought by Naim Attallah CBE from Garrard in the 1980s, and through his friendship with Princess Diana, he loaned it to her several times over several years. It is understood that the cross was only ever worn by the Princess, and following her death, it was never seen in public again until now.
✝️We can’t wait to see Kim flaunt this historic Cross!

Chain Reaction!
Italian Chains are rooted in a rich tradition of Italian jewellery history; and in the early century the Italian goldsmith handcrafted different types and varieties of chains. However, with the advancement in innovation, technology and infrastructure; machines have taken over chain making procedure resulting in improved production with highly detailed geometries.

At Vicenzaoro T.Gold, the International Show for machinery; I saw a machine used for making chains and alternate chains by Stilmec. 
Watch the entire video to view the procedure. “The wire passes through the machine and is cut depending on the design. Then the rings are formed and soldered to make the chains.”

𝐀𝐧𝐜𝐢𝐞𝐧𝐭 𝐉𝐞𝐰𝐞𝐥𝐥𝐞𝐫𝐲 𝐦𝐚𝐤𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐭𝐞𝐜𝐡𝐧𝐢𝐪𝐮𝐞𝐬!

Jewellery has been an important part of cultures across the globe since the early century. With the development of new-age machinery and technology, there has been an appreciation and revival of ancient art forms in jewellery making; that has lasted as a testimony to complex and time-consuming craftsmanship.
I am briefly sharing the Ancient jewellery-making techniques which, even today are an inspiration to modern contemporary designers.
✨𝐂𝐚𝐦𝐞𝐨: In a cameo, the design projects out of the background and is considered a relief image where the sculpted elements raise above the background plane. Cameos are referred to as a “positive” carving.
✨ 𝗜𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗴𝗹𝗶𝗼: In the Intaglio technique, images are carved or engraved in gemstones leaving a hollow impression in the untouched background. 
✨ 𝐅𝐢𝐥𝐢𝐠𝐫𝐞𝐞: This is one of the most delicate types of jewellery metalwork. Filigree uses precious metals, like gold and silver, in art pieces created with small detailed beads and twisted thin wires rolled into spirals and placed according to the design. This ancient technique creates artworks with the finest beauty, often giving us the impression of being made with lace. 
*** More in Caption***

These ancient and traditional methods of jewellery making are a reminder of the proverb, ‘Old is gold’!

Visit to #TopkapiPalace 🇹🇷
#ImperialTreasury of #OttomanSultan🤴🏻
Part 1 of 11
Visiting museums has always been an enriching experience. During my recent visit to Istanbul, I visited the Topkapi Palace Museum (Turkish Topkapı Sarayı Müzesi) in the Fatih district of Istanbul in Turkey and witnessed Ottoman Empire’s elaborate jewels, objects, clothing, weapons, armour, miniatures, religious relics, and a lot more!

After the conquest of Istanbul in 1453, the construction of Topkapı Palace, began in 1460 by Ottoman Sultan Fatih Sultan Mehmet and took nearly 18 years to complete. The palace became the administrative, educational and artistic centre of the Sultans of the Ottoman Empire for nearly four hundred years. It was given the name Topkapı, meaning Cannon Gate, in the 19th century. After the founding of the Republic of Turkey, on April 3, 1924, it was converted into a museum Topkapi Palace. Since 1985, it has been included in the UNESCO World Heritage List, and for good reason - this is a truly unique place and an outstanding monument of Islamic architecture and culture in general! 
Stay tuned for more interesting facts about the Topkapi Palace Museum.

Visit to #TopkapiPalace🇹🇷
#ImperialTreasury of #OttomanSultan🤴🏻
Part 5 of 11
Let’s dive a little into history; the Ottoman Empire was ruled by 36 different Sultans for over 600 years; which accounts for many important thrones. One of the most important thrones in the museum that caught my attention is the 17th-century Sultan Ahmed I throne.

It is made of walnut wood, with its entire surface decorated with a mosaic of mother-of-pearl and tortoiseshell. The vegetal decoration of floral motifs is a great example of Ottoman art achieved during the 11th / 17th centuries. The throne has an emerald and gold pendant hanging down in the middle of the dome.  And at the very top of the dome, there is a clock case in the form of a lantern. 

This throne is one of many objects which display the wealth of the Ottoman Palace.

In 1585, the Ottoman Sultan Murad III was gifted a magnificent throne made of gold-plated walnut wood and studded with 957 peridots in rosette mounts which could be dismantled into ten separate parts. 💙 As the name indicates, the blue Kashmir sapphire was discovered in the Padar portion of Kashmir. 
💙 Kashmir sapphires are renowned for their brilliance and strong saturation of velvet blue, which is reminiscent of the colour of a peacock’s neck. Weekend glow with Paraiba Tourmaline at @bftgems 

The Paraiba tourmaline necklace by @bftgems inspired me to present to you some important facts about the gem stone.
✨Paraiba tourmaline is the most valuable tourmaline variety due to its attractive colour, saturation and rarity.
✨The rare gemstone was first discovered in the Paraiba state of Brazil and are the most expensive and valuable variety of tourmaline.
✨Paraiba Tourmaline is popular for its unique range of blue-green colours and property to sparkle in a fairly low amount of light. A high concentration of copper present in the gemstones results in blue and green undertones, while manganese gives violet and red hues. To create a flawless blue Paraiba gem, the manganese section is removed using the burning technique.

Do you want a detailed series on Paraiba Tourmaline? Let me know in the comments.

Today, I discovered a very unique concept in jewellery manufacturing known as Electroforming.

It is a jewelry process where multiple layers of metals are allowed to build up, or “form” onto a surface. The artist can control where the metal will form on the jewellery piece by first painting the pattern on the item with special, electro-conductive paint. When the item is suspended in a plating tank, a current is supplied to it that allows the metal to start “forming” where the paint has been applied. Once the electroforming has reached the desired thickness and effect, the final coat of gold is plated.
The result is an extremely lightweight jewel! 

Featured above is a crocodile inspired necklace and bracelet by @innova_jewellery.

Wishing everyone a very Happy Easter with this 2.2 million dollar; “The Dragon Egg” which was created to commemorate the 10th anniversary of The Game of Thrones.
✨This work of art is co-designed by Designer, Liisa Tallgren and Michele Clapton, the Emmy®️ and BAFTA®️ winning costume designer from HBO®️’s Game of Thrones.
✨Weighing about 2.3 pounds, the Mother of Dragons-worthy egg is adorned with 2,160 round brilliant-cut white diamonds, 696 round faceted sapphires in three shades of pink; 547 round faceted rubies and 85 pear-and marquise-shaped Mozambique rubies and all fit for the First of Her Name, Breaker of Chains and Queen of the Andals and the First Men.
✨The shell is moulded from sheets of 18-karat white gold, and the egg’s pattern are drawn free-form and then engraved directly onto the material. The sparkling guilloche enamel scales were made from crushed light blue, grey, mauve and violet glass that was made into a paste, then layered, fired and re-polished.
✨An 18-karat white gold dragon tail wraps around the base, which is adorned with white diamonds and moonstones and contains a twisting mechanism of moving joints and linkages that required a “time-consuming” design process.
✨The objet opens to reveal yet another egg made of three 18-karat gold blades that each represents Drogon, Rhaegal and Viserion. The interior egg’s inner shells are finished with pear and marquise-shaped rubies, all surrounded by a pavé of hundreds of pink sapphires and white diamonds.
✨The heart of the egg is a pear-cut ruby that sits atop a removable white gold crown, which can be removed and attached as a pendant.

#CoronationRegalia ✨
All about the Royal Coronation!

With a few days to go for the Royal Coronation, let’s know about the ceremonial objects used in the Coronation. 
👑The Coronation Regalia refers to the ceremonial objects and attire used in the coronation of a monarch. These sacred and secular objects symbolise the service and responsibilities of the monarch. Coronation Regalia typically include a crown, sceptre, orb, sword, and other items of symbolic significance.

Featured above are Regalia to be used at the Coronation of The King and The Queen Consort.
✨Image 2: St Edward’s Crown will be used to crown His Majesty The King at Westminster Abbey on 6th May. The crown is topped with an orb and a cross, symbolising the Christian world, and is made up of a solid gold frame set with rubies, amethysts, sapphires, garnet, topazes and tourmalines. The crown has a velvet cap with an ermine band. St Edward’s Crown was worn by Queen Elizabeth II at the Coronation in 1953. 
✨Image 3: Queen Mary’s Crown has been chosen by The Queen Consort for the Coronation.
✨Image 4: The Imperial State Crown, or Crown of State, is the crown the monarch exchanges for St Edward's Crown at the end of the Coronation Service. The Imperial State Crown is also used on ceremonial occasions, such as the State Opening of Parliament. 
***More in the comments***

As part of the @royalcollectiontrust, the Regalia are held in trust by the Monarch on behalf of the nation.

Are you excited to view the Coronation ceremony? Let me know in the comments.

👑Head Ornaments worn by the royal authority reflected their power, righteousness, victory, triumph and identified an individual’s political hierarchy. The more heavy and bejewelled the head ornament, the higher the ranking of the wearer.

#CartierAndWoman 
Cartier has been one of the favourite jewellers to the Indian Maharaja & Maharani’s. The close bond between Cartier and India was most apparent during the Art Deco period, and resulted in two types of jewels: the Indian gems redesigned in the Cartier Western style for the maharajas, and the ‘India-inspired’ jewels presented to Cartier’s Western clientele.

👉Here is a good news for jewellery enthusiasts in Hong Kong or planning a trip to Hong Kong. 
✨The new special exhibition “Cartier and Women” is the first major exhibition on the role and influence of women in the history of Cartier. This exceptional exhibition showcases approximately 300 stunning treasures created by Cartier from the 19th century to the present day, such as jewellery, timepieces, precious objects, accessories and archival records.

The exhibition runs from 14 April to 14 August 2023.

#Coronation2023
The necklace that Queen Camilla is wearing is the iconic Coronation Necklace. It was designed by Garrard for Queen Victoria in 1858.

The magnificent necklace is considered an heirloom of The Crown and has been worn by every Queen for the coronation. Most recently it was worn by Queen Elizabeth II when she was crowned in 1953.
It is made from 25 graduated brilliant diamonds taken from old garter badges and the hilt of a ceremonial sword, and a 22.48-carat Lahore Diamond.
No wonder it is priceless!

Riyadh International Luxury Week!
Bahrain natural pearls!
My first interaction with Mr Ahmed Matar of @pearlbiography was in 2021 when I conducted an Insta Live with him. It was a pleasure to meet him in person and view his natural Bahrain pearl collection at the Riyadh Luxury Week. 
✨Featured above is a traditional 21 Karat Bahraini  gold necklace made with intricate detailing and Bahrain natural pearls and a turquoise pendant. In Bahrain, turquoise holds a special place in the local culture and is incorporated into various aspects of life, including traditional jewelry, adornments, and even architectural elements. The vibrant blue-green hue of turquoise is believed to ward off evil spirits and bring good fortune and prosperity.

A few highlights of Bahrain’s natural pearls are:
👉Bharain has a long history in Natural Pearl fishing and is currently the only country in the world, which by law, bans the trade of cultured pearls.
👉The government of Bahrain is currently reviving the natural pearl fishing and its heritage by encouraging people to go pearl diving and enacting fishing regulations.
👉Bahraini pearls are most highly-priced due to their rare exceptional lustre, which is the result of a combination of the freshwater springs inside the sea water. The deeper waters reveal white pearls with pinkish overtones that are not seen in other types of pearls.
👉Natural Pearls in the Arabian Gulf are graded on 5 factors which are: Size, Shape, Color, Lustre and the Surface Condition of the pearl.

These precious gifts from nature are extremely rare! Finding a special pearl demands not only patience & faith but involves a lot of hard work and effort!

✨Las Vegas Diaries✨
Renu at The Las Vegas Antique Jewelry & Watch Show.
It’s always a delight to meet my friends at @paulfisherjewelry and view their exceptional antique jewels! 
👸Featured above is a Victorian Era Trembling Tiara which can be assembled as a tiara as well as a brooch. 
👉Tremblant jewelry, is a type of jewelry that features movable elements or components that tremble with the wearer’s movement. It was particularly popular during the 18th and 19th centuries. The key characteristic of trembling jewelry is the use of small springs or wires that connect the gemstones or decorative elements to the main structure of the piece. The movement enhances the sparkle and brilliance of gemstones and add liveliness to the jewelry!

Emerald and diamond brilliance is seen together in these uniquely crafted special triangular-shaped Zambian emeralds; flaunted by delicate baguette diamond strings by @house_of_umrao @jckevents.

Allow me to highlight some key points about Zambian Emeralds!
💚 Zambia is known for producing emeralds in larger sizes, this makes Zambian emeralds a desirable choice for collectors seeking bold and impressive gemstone jewellery.
💚 Zambian emeralds are renowned for their deep and vibrant green hue. They often exhibit a rich, saturated colour with a slightly bluish undertone.
💚 Zambian emeralds tend to have fewer inclusions and a high level of transparency, allowing light to pass through and enhance their natural beauty.
💚 These emeralds often display a remarkable level of brilliance, thanks to their excellent light reflection and refraction properties. 
💚 Additionally, Zambia has made considerable efforts to enforce ethical mining practices, ensuring fair labour conditions and environmental sustainability. This commitment adds to the appeal of Zambian emeralds.
Let me know which origin emerald is your favourite: Zambian or Colombian!

Monday with Micromosaic Technique Jewellery! 
✨At the recently concluded @by_couture show in Las Vegas, I was delighted to discover gold and gemstone jewels made in Italy using @sicisjewels signature micromosaic technique. This remarkable and ancient technique, the brand’s signature, uses tiny glass fragments with varied shapes, and is set one by one by hand with precision to create colourful and fascinating designs; the result is extraordinary wearable art. 
✨Featured above is a Concentric micromosaic circles necklace embellished in diamonds, sapphires and tanzanites.
✨The mission of Sicis Jewels is to reinterpret the charm and the mystery of ancient Micromosaic techniques and make them into contemporary jewellery!

Isn’t it a mix of all things modern?

Have you seen the yesteryear stomacher jewellery? I was delighted to see the 1870 English/ French stomacher at @spicer_warin in @usantiqueshows.
✨Stomacher jewellery, also known as a stomacher brooch or stomacher ornament, originated in the 17th century and remained popular until the early 19th century. These bejewelled ornaments are worn on the front of a dress or bodice and are embellished with gemstones, precious metals, embroidery, or other decorative elements.
✨Stomacher jewellery were considered a status symbol and a way for women to display their wealth and fashion sense. The designs could vary widely, ranging from simple and elegant to extravagant and intricate. 
✨These jewels fell out of fashion as dress styles changed in the 19th century, but they are still admired and collected today as historical artefacts and are examples of fine craftsmanship.
So tell me, would you like to wear one?

#RoyalThaiJewels 🇹🇭
Part 3 of 18
The Five Royal Regalias!
The Royal Regalia of Thailand refers to the collection of sacred and ceremonial items used in the country's royal ceremonies and coronations. During King Maha Vajiralongkorn's coronation on May 4, 2019, the monarch was presented with five royal regalias, treated as symbols of kingship, marking the legitimacy of his reign.
1️⃣ Great Crown of Victory (Phra Maha Phichai Mongkut) and Umbrella: This crown is the most important symbol of the Thai monarchy. It is traditionally used for coronation ceremonies and is adorned with precious gems and diamonds. At the tip of the cone-shaped crown is a large diamond from Kolkata called “Phra Maha Wichian Mani”.
The coronation is only considered complete when the new king is presented with the royal nine-tiered umbrella, which is considered the most sacred object by the country’s Ministry of Culture. 
2️⃣ Sword of Victory (Phra Saeng Khan Chai Sri): The sword is a symbol of the King's military prowess and leadership. It is ornamented in gold enamel, precious gems and decorated with intricate designs.
3️⃣ The Royal Sceptre (Than Phra Kon): The staff is crafted from Javanese Cassia wood, with a gilded trident as the finial and an iron hilt enamelled with gold.
4️⃣ The Royal Fan and Fly Whisk ( Walawichani)
It was made in the reign of King Rama I as a symbol to repel any negative forces that might adversely affect the kingdom. 
5️⃣ The Royal Slippers (Chalong Phrabat Choeng Ngon): The royal slippers are in the form of an open-heeled slipper with the front curling up to a point.

The Thai royalty has a long history of acquiring and commissioning exquisite jewellery. Today I would like to highlight the spectacular Royal Thai Tiara, worn by the Thai Queen Consort for almost 70 years on multiple occasions.

✨The Royal Thai Tiara was created by Van Cleef & Arpels in 1960 with white and yellow diamonds set in a traditional Thai style. The story goes; the center large yellow diamonds were not sent to Paris and instead, zircons of the exact size were handed to the VCA to enable the mounting to be made precisely. The large yellow diamonds were set after the Tiara arrived in Thailand. 
✨The yellow diamond and floral motif can also be removed from the frame, to be worn as a bandeau, necklace, or bracelet.

Episode 1: Pearl Harbour!
Mir Osman Ali Khan Siddiqi, Asaf Jah VII, the last Nizam of Hyderabad had the most varied collection of Natural Pearls jewellery and the pearls he had accumulated could fill up the “Olympic Size Pool.”

💭Are you wondering how did the wealthiest man of the 19th century, build up his pearl collection? 
✨The story goes, The Nizam loved natural pearls, so when the pearl dealers came to Hyderabad along with their collection to offer; each pearl being of a different colour, shape, size and make; made it difficult to design a jewelry. Therefore, The Nizam kept on collecting Natural Pearls, until they could be symmetry crafted into an ornament. This created a market of pearls in Hyderabad, giving it the title, “City Of Pearls.” Even today, Hyderabad is the market for the trading of Natural Pearls.

What goes into the making of Polki Jewellery?
Polki jewellery holds significant cultural and historical importance in India. It is a traditional form of jewellery that originated in the 18th century, during the Mughal era and is very popular among jewellery aficionados.

Allow me to briefly highlight the manufacturing procedure of Polki Jewellery:
✨Polki jewellery is created using a specialized technique known as Kundan; in this procedure; the skilled artisans meticulously set uncut diamonds (polki) in intricate gold or silver settings, often embellished with precious gemstones, pearls, and enamel work. The craftsmanship involved in making polki jewelry represents the rich heritage of Indian jewelry-making traditions.

I came across this rare and historic Golconda Diamond necklace by @rare_mkv at @jasrajasthan. Allow me to highlight what makes Golconda diamonds special.

💎Golconda diamonds are highly prized gemstones that were mined in The Golconda mines, located near the city of Hyderabad and these diamonds are highly sought after by collectors, gem enthusiasts, and connoisseurs of fine jewelry. 
💎Due to their rarity and historical significance, Golconda diamonds often command high prices at auctions and are considered valuable investments.
👉Did you know: The territory of The Golconda mine belonged to the Nizam of Hyderabad, and all Golconda diamonds known today were mined in his kingdom.
Out of 38 diamond mines of India, 23 were located in the Golconda Sultanate, making it the ‘Diamond Capital’ of the past. It was considered a matter of pride by any ruler to be the owner of one of the Golconda Diamonds.

Sadly, the Golconda mines have been depleted for centuries, and the availability of Golconda diamonds is extremely limited. Many of the Golconda diamonds in circulation today are historical gems that have been passed down through generations or have been part of renowned gem collections.

Rare shades of Tanzanite! 
If you think that the gemstone Tanzanite is only available on shades of blue-violet, this post will make you think otherwise.

Tanzanite is a gemstone renowned for its vivid blue-violet colour, and is primarily found in various shades of blue, ranging from light sky blue to deep violet-blue. 
However, it’s important to note that any tanzanite with colours significantly different from the blue-violet spectrum is considered rare and valuable. These exceptional tanzanite stones, often referred to as “Fancy Tanzanite,” can exhibit colors such as green, yellow, or brown and are highly sought after by collectors and gem enthusiasts due to its rarity and distinctive beauty! 💜💙♥️💛

I saw these rare shades, that captivate the beauty and rarity for the first time by Ag Gems Pvt Ltd @aggemspvtltd at @jasrajasthan and am thrilled to share them with all of you!

Thailand has a long history of royalty and a deep appreciation for gemstones. 

Emeralds, in particular have been used in royal regalia and jewellery for centuries, and their popularity has endured through generations. It is also believed that the Thai Royal Family had historical connections with countries known for their emerald deposits, such as Colombia and Zambia that may have influenced the acquisition of emeralds within the royal family. The queens of the Chakri Dynasty loved their emeralds, and they adorned emerald jewels in the form of necklaces, belts and brooches!

The Spectacular Pocket Watch!

For all those who have been following me, know that I have been a great admirer of the jewels of Nizam of Hyderabad. And I was extremely delighted to find the Pocket Watch passed down from the Nizam Of Hyderabad himself to the Shiv Narayan family.

Here’s what makes this pocket watch a collector’s item:
✨Nizam of Hyderabad graciously wore his Pocket Watch made between the 18-19 century, with multiple attached chains to allow them to be secured to a waistcoat, lapel, or belt loops, to prevent them from falling.
#DidYouKnow : European influences, essentially from Paris and London, were particularly strong in the early 20th century. One of the instances can be seen in the use of pocket watches, which ultimately became a part of the ceremonial regalia of the Indian royalty.

Part 2 of 12
The life story of Ambaji Shinde: The Greatest Jewellery Designer of the Century!

From humble beginnings in Mapusa, Goa, to designing jewels for International royalty, here are snippets from the life story of Ambaji Shinde, who is hailed as the ‘greatest jewellery designer of the century.’
✨Ambaji Shinde was born in 1917 in the tiny state of Goa. He was drawn towards decorative arts at an early age. He came to Mumbai in 1934 to attend the J. J. School of Arts.
✨His first job was at Narottamdas Jhaveri where he designed ornate silverware, trophies and jewellery. He was later hired by Nanubhai Jhaveri in 1941 where he worked for nearly 20 years, designing jewellery for the Maharajas!

✨Image 2: JJ School of Arts, Bombay
✨Image 3: Nanubhai Jhaveri

#RoyalTreasuresWithRenu
Episode 4: The famous Indore Pears.
Continuing with our series on the Royal jewels from the treasury of Maharajas! 

Today, I will highlight the story of the legendary and the famous Indore Pears! 

✨HH Maharaja Tukoji Rao III; Holkar 13, a great jewellery collector purchased more than 1200 pieces during his reign and one of the most magnificent pieces of jewellery purchased by him was the incredible pear-shaped diamonds of 46.95-carat & 46.70-carat known as Indoor Pears during his visit to @chaumetofficial salon Paris in 1913. 
✨The story goes that a close friendship between HH Yashwant Rao Holkar II and Jean Goulet, a member of the Mauboussin was brewing. The Indore Pears was redesigned to a long necklace with baguette diamonds chain, two emerald cut diamonds, a large octagonal emerald and two Indore Pears framed along with a pear-cut diamond by Mauboussin. 
✨In 1946, HH Yashwant Rao Holkar II; Holkar 14 sold the diamonds to Harry Winston, who recut them to 44.62 and 44.18 carats, and Harry Winston designed a baguette-cut diamond necklace suspending the Indore Pears. The necklace was sold and repurchased by Harry Winston several times.
✨Currently, the Indore Pears are a part of the private collection of Arab jeweller Robert Mouawad and are set as a pair of pendant earrings.

👉Follow my series #MaharajaofIndore on my #InstagramGuide section for more details. And let me know which #RoyalTreasure would you like me to feature next!

Let’s continue our series on the jewels designed by Ambaji Shinde! 

The making of the prestigious long baguette necklace!
✨In 1938, Ambaji Shinde got an assignment to design jewels for the coronation of Maharaja of Baroda. He designed a stunning natural diamond necklace made with long baguettes beautifully modulated, mimicking two paper rolls cascading effortlessly into twirls. This magnificent necklace was adorned by Rajmata Vijaya Raje Scindia.
✨The story goes that the original idea of using large extraordinarily long baguette-cut diamonds was first conceptualised by Nanubhai Jhaveri and Shinde translated Nanubhai’s concept into a series of beautiful working designs with 10 to 12 variants.

Part 4 of 12
The master crafter and his masterpieces!

Ambaji Shinde developed his exclusive style with Nanubhai Jhaveri. His diamond jewellery designs were admired and adorned by Indian maharajas like the Nizam of Hyderabad, the Kings of Saudi Arabia, Nepal, and Ethiopia, to name a few.

Allow me to share a few interesting stories!
✨In the early 1900s when the Indian maharajas started travelling abroad and were more inclined towards Western-style designs and lifestyle; Shinde modified his designs to produce exquisite settings centred around larger and rare gems. 
✨After India’s independence, Nanubhai Jewelers purchased huge quantities of diamonds from maharajas and Shinde created a masterpiece collection of earrings, necklaces, bracelets, and rings that were purchased by the maharajas of Gwalior, and Harry Winston
Akshay Chava

In March 1946, Prince Aga Khan III ordered Shind to create a white Sari, with more than 1,200 diamonds for his third wife; to commemorate the 60th anniversary of his reign,

The historic partnership of Ambaji Shinde with Harry Winston 

✨In my previous post, I mentioned that after India’s independence, Nanubhai Jewelers purchased huge quantities of diamonds from Maharajas in 1953 and Ambaji Shinde created a masterpiece collection. Impressed by Shinde’s work, Harry Winston offered him a job at Harry Winston and Shinde's journey led him to New York in 1959, where his collaboration with Winston flourished. 
✨Together, they pioneered groundbreaking "cluster" diamond settings, introducing a three-dimensional aesthetic. The innovative designs and the historic partnership of Shinde with Harry Winston led to the creation of jewels for important royal families and popular celebrities.
Here are a few glimpses from Shinde’s historical journey with Harry Winston.

Stone suspending in the air!

✨An important part of Shinde’s work was the re-faceting of gemstones. At Harry Winston, Ambaji Shinde adopted a new style that used little metal and fused the idea of “stone suspending in the air”.
✨HM Queen Elizabeth ll was seen wearing some of the most exquisite jewellery throughout her lifetime which included one of the pieces designed by Ambaji Shinde. This diamond necklace was exclusively designed for Queen Elizabeth ll which HM wore at different royal events.

Thank you Reema Keswani @golcondajewelry A.V. Shinde's only authorized biographer, for the incredible research.

#AmbajiShinde 
Part 8 of 11
Recreation of the Historic Indore Pears!

✨Ambaji Shinde had the opportunity to recreate designs for some of the most exceptional diamonds. One of the classic examples is the recreation of design for the historic Indore Pears, in 1976.
✨Allow me to share the story of the Indore pears: In 1946, HH Yashwant Rao Holkar II; Holkar 14 sold the diamonds to Harry Winston, who recut them to 44.62 and 44.18 carats. Harry Winston designed a baguette-cut diamond necklace suspending the Indore Pears. The necklace was sold and repurchased by Harry Winston. Currently, the Indore Pears are a part of the private collection of Arab jeweller Robert Mouawad set as a pair of pendant earrings.
What a turn in history!

Thank you Reema Keswani @golcondajewelry, A.V. Shinde's only authorized biographer, for the incredible research.

Part 11 of 11
Celebrating the legacy of Ambaji Shinde!

✨The kind-hearted and generous Ambaji Shinde gave more than five thousand original sketches and studies to the Gemological Institute of America for future students of jewellery design. 
✨In an interview in 2011, CEO of the Harry Winston said: The art of Shinde continues to thrive. Much of what you see in our archives remains an incredible source of inspiration for our designers. There are over 100,000 original design projects by Ambaji Shinde, in addition to those that have been implemented, and several dozen works in our collection. Shinde’s heritage is often a creative spark that we use to create new masterpieces of jewellery from Harry Winston for the generations to come.
✨To celebrate the legacy of Shinde, Harry Winston launched an exclusive watch collection after him; The Premier Shinde Collection in 2015. The timepieces are adorned with decorative dials that reinterpret the dials feature, and motifs that merge and represent two of his classic designs, a necklace and a tiara.
Images:
What a way to pay tribute to such an amazing, talented powerhouse!

Gemstone Trends from the world’s Gemstone Capital: BANGKOK! 🇹🇭

It was a pleasure being a part of the 68th edition of Bangkok Gems and Jewelry Fair, which is Thailand’s largest and Asia’s longest-celebrated gems and jewellery trade show. Today’s content features 5 trending gemstones @rmcgems 
💙 Paraiba Tourmaline: Paraiba Tourmaline’s unique color, rarity, and desirability have solidified its position as one of the most popular and sought-after gemstones in the world of fine jewellery and gemstone collecting.
❤️ Rubellite: Red has always been a very popular colour and rubellite is known for its exceptional colour saturation. Since rubellite crystals are often found in larger sizes, these gemstones are cut into big sizes and used for creating statement jewelry.
🧡Morganite: These gemstones have a delicate and feminine approach. From pale baby pink to a deeper rose, they resemble the delicate petals of a blooming flower or soft sunset. Morganite’s combination of attractive colour, affordability, durability, and versatility makes it a very popular choice!
💙Aquamarine: The alluring blue colour, brings out the feeling of calmness and these gemstones have been popularly used in engagement rings, and necklaces and are considered heirloom-worthy, passed down through generations.
❤️🧡💜 Multi-colour tourmaline: Multiple-color tourmaline is cherished for its captivating and distinct colour zoning. These gemstones offer versatility in jewellery design and are preferred by collectors looking for unique and colourful gemstone jewellery.

⏱️Watches inspired by The Ottoman Empire!

The Ottoman Empire ruled over Istanbul from the late 13th century until the early 20th century, and had a very significant influence on Jewellery making with the use of exquisite craftsmanship, symbolic elements, and incorporation of precious materials. This influence is still evident in contemporary jewellery design, and pieces inspired by Ottoman traditions which are treasured by collectors and enthusiasts around the world!

👉At the Istanbul Jewelery Show, I discovered these timeless watches inspired by the Ottoman Empire, by Arden’s Fine Jewelers, that reminded me of the exquisite watches and clocks I saw during my visit to the Topkapi Palace Musem, a must-visit museum for all jewellery enthusiast!

All about Mozambique Ruby!

I have been an admirer of all things rare and beautiful, and at the recently concluded Istanbul Jewelry Show, this magnificent natural diamonds and Mozambique Ruby necklace; crafted with meticulous detailing by @dilajewellery had me captivated!

👉Allow me to highlight a few facts about Mozambique’s Ruby:
✨As the name suggests, these rubies are found in Mozambique and are known for their vibrant and intense red color.
✨Mozambique has produced rubies of various sizes, including larger stones, which are rare in other ruby-producing regions; these larger, high-quality rubies make a great invetsment and are used in high jewellery.
✨Mozambique rubies often exhibit excellent transparency, allowing for the passage of light and the display of their color; and this transparency is the most important factor that accounts for the overall beauty and value of the gemstone.

So if Ruby red is your favourite gemstone, Mozambique ruby is the one for you!

Part 4 of 17
One of the most prized jewels I saw during my visit to the Victoria and Albert Museum was Queen Victoria’s Diamond and Sapphire Coronet.

👑This coronet was designed by Prince Albert for his wife, Queen Victoria in 1840 and is one of the most prominent jewels worn by her. One of the key highlights of the coronet is that it’s extremely flexible and can not just be worn closed circular but also open at the back, as seen in the video. 👑In 1842, Queen Victoria wore the coronet in a famous portrait made by Franz Xaver Winterhalter’s and after 20 years, she wore it again as a crown to the open Parliament for the first time after her husband Albert’s death; she carried her crown on a cushion.

What a creative way to use one single piece of jewellery!

Fabergé Presentation Case 🎁
The Royal Family, often used presentation cases to store important items of historical, ceremonial, and personal importance. These presentation cases were made with meticulous detailing and incorporated with symbols or emblems associated with the monarchy. 
🎁Featured above is an exquisite Fabergé, presentation case from Russia, St Petersburg 1899-1903, made in gold, brilliant cut diamonds, and enamel. We can see the crowned cipher of Nicholas II on the lid. 

There is a unique charm and beauty to all things belonging to royalty, whether it is jewellery or a presentation case!  Impressive, isn’t it?

#VictoriaAndAlbertMuseum
Part 9 of 17
One of the masterpieces I saw during my visit to the Victoria & Albert Museum is the enamel ring tray made by Eugène Feuillâtre, who was the head of the enamelling studio of René Lalique. It is a magnificent example of Plique-à-jour enamel, a technique discovered by Parisian goldsmiths in the 19th century.

✨In this technique; enamel is applied in cells with no backing which allows the light to shine through the transparent or translucent enamel. This enamelling technique is used in the rendering of leaves, flowers, insect wings and gained new heights during the Art Nouveau period.

Vintage Signed Jewels!
It was a pleasure meeting the Yafa Signed Jewel’s family at the Gem Geneve and admiring their rare and exclusive collection of vintage Signed jewels by Cartier, VCA and Bulgari.

👉So what are SIGNED JEWELS?
Signed jewels are jewels that bear a signature in full or a maker’s mark from the jeweller that made them. The marks are often very small and engraved or stamped on inconspicuous areas of the metal, usually on the sides or back of the jewel. Sometimes, they also have an engraved inventory number which can be traced back into the archive of the jeweller that made them, revealing the exact date they were made, the client they were made for and the numbers and carat weights of the gems incorporated into the jewel.

Sarah Ho @sarahhojewellery is known for creating contemporary jewellery from antique gemstones and recycled gold. 

During the recently concluded @jewelleryarabiabahrain I discovered a stunning pair of earrings and ring made from Clam pearls and antique Australian Opal. 

Allow me highlight characteristics of Clam Pearl:
✨Clam pearls are rarer compared to traditional natural pearls.
✨ The rarity of clam pearls is attributed to the specific conditions required for their formation; and the fact that not all clams produce pearls, makes these pearls extremely rare!
✨The value of the Clam Pearl is influenced by size, shape, color, and luster!
No wonder clam pearls make for such an exceptional jewellery.

Decoding the mystery behind the Mystery setting!

A spectacular 5.43 cts Fancy Vivid Yellow diamond and emerald “Kallima” ring by Van Cleef & Arpels, was recently auctioned at @sothebysjewels Sotheby’s Magnificent Jewels and Noble Jewels auction In Geneva.
2 reasons to make this ring special.
1️⃣ Van Cleef and Arpels patented the Mystery setting technique in 1933, which was only on flat surfaces, and in 1938, they created the setting on curved 3-dimensional surfaces such as the wing of the butterfly wings here. 
2️⃣ Emeralds are the rare coloured stone to be used in Mystery Settings as they are very fragile gemstones and more skill and time are needed to create this technique as compared to ruby and sapphire.

No wonder this ring personifies magnificence in more ways than one!

#VictoriaAndAlbertMuseum 
Part 12 of 17
One of the much-loved antique jewellery is the bodice ornament. The evolution of this wearable art originated in the mid-17th century when changes in fashion introduced new styles of jewellery. During this time, the most impressive jewels were often large bodice or breast ornaments, which had to be pinned or stitched to stiff dress fabrics. They were frequently paired with a necklace or other piece of jewellery that hung below. 

✨Featured above is a great example of the Bodice ornament, made in the Netherlands, about 1680-1700; embellished in rose-cut diamonds set in silver and hessonite garnet ribbons twisting through the silver foliage, with coloured foil beneath the gems to enhance their rich colour. 

This is a piece of art and heart worn as jewellery.

A garland-style ruby and diamond studded Tiarawas made in 1913 by Cartier.

🫅The inspiration came from ornament books of the 17th and 18th centuries which were re-published in the second half of the 19th century, and from the study of the architecture and ironwork of Paris and the palaces of Versailles and Fontainebleau.

No wonder it’s an artistic piece of beauty!

The vintage Diamond and Sapphire Necklace!! 

💙Lady Cory’s Sapphire and Diamond Necklace, 1850-1930 is made in European-cut diamonds set in silver and mounted around gold-set.
💙Originally, the piece was one long necklace which was designed to be worn in conjunction with a jewelled stomacher. In 1930, Lady Cory had the necklace adapted into a shorter, double-strand piece. The excess links were made into earrings, making a valuable and gorgeous parure.

Isn’t it difficult to describe the beauty and allure of this vintage necklace?

#VictoriaAndAlbertMuseum 
Part 15 of 17
Londonary jewels 
An esteemed collection of Aristocratic Jewellery 

The Londonderry Jewels, originally stemming from the Down Diamonds in India during the 18th century, represent an esteemed collection of aristocratic jewellery in Britain.
✨This includes the renowned Londonderry Tiara, created around 1885, composed of brilliant-cut diamonds set in silver on a gold frame, and later enhanced with arches to function as a crown during Queen Victoria’s Diamond Jubilee. 
✨The collection also comprises stunning earrings from 1915, a necklace featuring brilliant-cut diamonds, a suite of amethysts gifted by Tsar Alexander I of Russia, a remarkable bow brooch from 1885, and a diamond stomacher made in 1854, crafted from diamonds sourced from the Londonderry Garter insignia and Castlereagh’s sword, which can be divided into three brooches.

#VictoriaAndAlbertMuseum 
Part 16 of 17
Stomacher or Breast jewels in the form of Bows and Flowers were worn on formal occasions in the 18th-century. These jewels were often attached to velvet ribbons; worn on sleeves, or in worn as hairpins. 
Did you know that stomachers were worn not only by women but also men in the 15th and 16th century?
An interesting piece of jewellery, isn’t it?

The Peridot Necklace!
Wrapping up my virtual tour inside the Victoria And Albert Museum’s jewellery section! 
💚This early to mid-19th-century Peridot necklace showcases the exquisite beauty of Peridot gemstones. 
💚Peridot is a gem known for its enchanting green hues, symbolizing renewal and abundance. The gemstones in this necklace are open-set in silver, allowing light to interact with their vibrant colours, and are  backed with gold to enhance their brilliance.
The three large central units of the necklace may have been a part of a tiara or another necklace.
